Alternatively, you can selectively add features from the articles below. The non-optional ones are highly recommended, and features are listed in roughly suggested order of implementation:
* '''Inbound''' (receiving mail to your server)
** [[Postfix/Blacklisting|Blacklisting]], or banning the work of spammers already identified by third parties
** Checksum-based systems
*** [[Postfix/DCC|Distributed Checksum Clearinghouse]], a global bulk mail detection system
*** [[Postfix/Razor|Vipul's Razor]]
** [[Postfix/Greylisting|Greylisting]], or delaying accepting mail from new senders (long enough for blacklists to kick in)
** [[Postfix/Miscellaneous anti-spam measures|Miscellaneous anti-spam measures]]
** Optional
***[[Postfix/policyd-weight|policyd-weight]], a weighted rejection policy daemon
***Investigate all of the various packages in <code>/usr/portage/mail-filter/</code>
* '''Outbound''' (sending mail to others from your server, and actually having it received)
** [[Postfix/SPF|Sender Policy Framework (SPF)]], to set IP address ranges allowed to send email from your domain
** [[Postfix/DKIM|DomainKeys Identified Mail (DKIM)]], to set cryptographic protection for outbound mail proving it is from your domain
** [[Postfix/DMARC|Domain-based Message Authentication, Reporting and Conformance (DMARC)]], to get feedback on issues third parties have processing mail you have sent, and to inform them how you'd prefer them to handle such issues
* Optional
**'''Relaying''' (sending mail on behalf of connecting clients to third-party servers)
*** [[Postfix/SASL|Simple Authentication and Security Layer (SASL)]], for identifying clients authorized to supply mail for relay
